{{India-reli-bio-stub}}

A '''hyperpower''' is a [[state (polity)|state]] that dominates all other states in every domain (i.e. military, culture, economy)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/hyperpower|title=Definition of 'hyperpower'|publisher=[[HarperCollins|Collins]]|website=[[Collins English Dictionary|Collins Dictionary]]|accessdate=February 11, 2018}}</ref> and is considered to be a step higher than a [[superpower]]. The term often refers to the [[United States|United States of America]] due to its status as the world's only current superpower; however, its possible status above that remains a topic of dispute.<ref name="To Paris">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/05/news/to-paris-us-looks-like-a-hyperpower.html|title=To Paris, U.S. Looks Like a 'Hyperpower'|work=[[The New York Times International Edition|International Herald Tribune]]|date=February 5, 1999|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=February 11, 2018}}</ref>
==History== The British journalist [[Peregrine Worsthorne]] coined the term in a ''[[The Sunday Telegraph|Sunday Telegraph]]'' article published March 3, 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordspy.com/words/hyper-power.asp|title=hyper-power|date=February 25, 2002|publisher=Logophilia Limited|last=McFedries|first=Paul|author-link=Paul McFedries|website=Word Spy|accessdate=February 11, 2018}}</ref> After the end of the [[Cold War]] with the [[Soviet Union]], some political commentators felt that a new term was needed to describe the United States' position (''[[Pax Americana]]'') as the lone superpower.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lonely Superpower or Unapologetic Hyperpower? |url=http://post.queensu.ca/~nossalk/papers/hyperpower.htm |first=Kim Richard|last=Nossal|author-link=Kim Richard Nossal|date=June 29, 1999|publisher=South African Political Studies Association|location=[[Saldanha, Western Cape]]|accessdate=November 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|quote=Now though, some people, in whose opinion the term "superpower" does not denote the actual dominance of the USA incisively enough, use the term "hyperpower".|first1=Erich|last1=Reiter|first2=Peter|last2=Hazdra|title=The Impact of Asian Powers on Global Developments|page=5|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]]|date=March 9, 2013|isbn=9-783-6621-3172-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/united-states/2004-07-01/history-and-hyperpower|title=History and the Hyperpower|last=Cohen|first=Eliot A.|author-link=Eliot A. Cohen|date=July 1, 2004|journal=[[Foreign Affairs]]|publisher=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]|accessdate=February 11, 2018}}</ref> French foreign minister [[Hubert Védrine]] popularized the term in 1998, because from France's position, the United States looked like a hyperpower, although the validity of classifying the United States in this way was disputed.<ref name="To Paris"/>
The term has also been applied retroactively to dominant states of the past. In her book ''[[Day of Empire|Day of Empire: How Hyperpowers Rise to Global Dominance—and Why They Fall]]'', American professor [[Amy Chua]] suggests that the [[Achaemenid Empire]], the [[Tang dynasty]], the [[Roman Empire]], the [[Mongol Empire]], the [[Ottoman Empire]], and the [[British Empire]] were successful examples of historical [[hegemons]]; the [[Spanish Empire|Spanish Monarchy]], [[Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere]], and [[Nazi Germany|Third Reich]] were counters; and she reflects on assertions that the United States is a modern hyperpower. In a historical context, it is usually understood to mean a power that greatly exceeds any others in its political environment along several axes; Rome did not dominate [[Sasanian Empire|Persia]], [[Ancient India]] or [[History of China|China]], but did dominate the entire Mediterranean area militarily, culturally, and economically.<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Day of Empire|Day of Empire: How Hyperpowers Rise to Global Dominance—and Why They Fall]]|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group]]|date=January 6, 2009|last=Chua|first=Amy|author-link=Amy Chua|isbn=9-780-3074-7245-8}}</ref>
