{{Infobox person | name = Ragnar Hovland | image = Ragnar Hovland Bjoernsonfestvalen 2006.jpg | alt = | caption = Hovland in 2006 | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age | 1952|4|15| df=y}} | birth_place = [[Bergen]], Norway | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = Norwegian | other_names = | occupation = novelist, essayist, poet and children's writer | known_for = | parents = | relations = [[Ragnvald Indrebø]] (grandfather) | awards = {{ubl | [[Brage Prize]] (1992)| [[Norwegian Critics Prize for Literature]] (2001)| [[Dobloug Prize]] (2008)| [[Bastian Prize|Bastian Prize for Children's and Young-Adult Books]] (2008) }} }}
'''Ragnar Hovland''' (born 15 April 1952 in [[Bergen]]) is a Norwegian novelist, essayist, poet, and writer of children's books.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Ragnar Hovland |first= |last= |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor-last=Bolstad | editor-first=Erik | editor-link= |publisher=Norsk nettleksikon |location=Oslo |url=https://snl.no/Ragnar_Hovland |language=Norwegian |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Ragnar Hovland |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Sverre |last=Tusvik |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=https://nbl.snl.no/Ragnar_Hovland | language=Norwegian |accessdate=6 July 2018}}</ref>
==Personal life== Hovland was born in [[Bergen]] to priest Håkon Hovland and schoolteacher Sigrid Indrebø, and grew up in [[Strandvik]] and [[Luster, Norway|Luster]]. He was married to Sabine Angelika Rolka from 1978 to 1992, and to Tove Olaug Bakke since 1996.<ref name =nbl/>
==Career== Hovland made his literary debut in 1979, with the novel ''{{ill|Alltid fleire dagar|nn}}''.<ref name =snl/> The book follows four young boys from secondary school to college. Their interests circle around [[rock music]], alcohol, a dose of politics and girls.<ref name=rottem>{{cite book |title=Norges Litteraturhistorie. Etterkrigslitteraturen |chapter= Ragnar Hovland &ndash; livet på veiene |pages=458–473 |first=Øystein |last=Rottem |authorlink=Øystein Rottem | |volume=3 |publisher=Cappelen |location=Oslo |year=1998 |language=Norwegian |isbn=82-02-16426-5 }}</ref>
He followed up with the [[short story]] collection ''{{ill|Vegen smal og porten trang|no}}'' (1981). The collection includes the stories "Dei siste beat-poetane i Midthordaland", where two wannabe poets are expelled from the gang and instead read their works for a herd of wet sheep; further "Sommarens blå flygel", where two young lovers are surprised by the boy's father, who expresses concern that they could catch a [[Common cold|cold]] since they lie naked on the ground. In the [[surrealistic]] story "Songen om Emilia", a young man finds a dead body on the floor three days in a row, and is unable to get rid of the corps, even if he pushes them into the cupboard every time.<ref name=rottem/>
The novel ''Sveve over vatna'' (1982) is set in Bergen, and the protagonist is a student who gets involved in various strange adventures.<ref name=rottem/>
He was awarded the [[Brage Prize]] in 1992 for the children's book ''Ein motorsykkel i natta''.<ref name=brage-former>{{cite web|url=http://www.brageprisen.no/tekster/tidligere.shtml|title=Tidligere vinnere av Brageprisen|work=|date=|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2008-10-14|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610082646/http://www.brageprisen.no/tekster/tidligere.shtml|archivedate=2008-06-10|df=}}</ref> He received the [[Norwegian Critics Prize for Literature]] in 2001, for the novel ''Ei vinterreise''.
