==External classification==

Beyond the traditionally recognized families of Southeast Asia, a number of [[Classification schemes for Southeast Asian languages|possible broader relationships]] have been suggested.

One of these is the "[[Sino-Caucasian]]" hypothesis of [[Sergei Starostin]], which posits that the [[Yeniseian languages]] and [[North Caucasian languages]] form a [[clade]] with Sino-Tibetan. The Sino-Caucasian hypothesis has been expanded by others to "[[Dené–Caucasian languages|Dené–Caucasian]]" to include the [[Na-Dené languages]] of North America, [[Burushaski language|Burushaski]], [[Basque language|Basque]] and, occasionally, [[Etruscan language|Etruscan]]. [[Edward Sapir]] had commented on a connection between Na-Dené and Sino-Tibetan.{{sfnp|Shafer|1952}} A narrower binary [[Dené–Yeniseian]] family has recently been well-received, though not conclusively demonstrated.

In contrast, [[Laurent Sagart]] proposes a [[Sino-Austronesian languages|Sino-Austronesian family]] with Sino-Tibetan and [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] (including [[Kra–Dai languages|Kra–Dai]] as a subbranch) as primary branches.{{sfnp|Sagart|2005}}
Stanley Starosta has extended this proposal with a further branch called "Yangzian" joining [[Hmong–Mien languages|Hmong–Mien]] and [[Austroasiatic languages|Austroasiatic]].{{sfnp|Starosta|2005}}

